s question, anthropologist Summerson Carr traces the charged interactions between counselors, clients, and case managers at "Fresh Beginnings," an addiction treatment program for homeless women in the midwestern United States. She shows that shelter, food, and even the custody of children hang in the balance of everyday therapeutic exchanges, such as clinical assessments, individual therapy sessions, and self-help meetings. Acutely aware of the high stakes of self-representation, experienced clients analyze and learn to effectively perform prescribed ways of speaking, a mimetic practice they call "flipping the script." As a clinical ethnography, Scripting Addiction examines how decades of clinical theorizing about addiction, language, self-knowledge, and sobriety is manifested in interactions between counselors and clients. As an ethnography of the contemporary United States, the book demonstrates the complex cultural roots of the powerful clinical ideas that shape therapeutic transactions--and by extension administrative routines and institutional dynamics--at sites such as "Fresh Beginnings."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAnthropology, CulturalvmethodszUnited States. 0aCommunication and culture. 0aCommunicationzUnited States. 0aCulturevSemiotic models. 0aCulturexSemiotic models. 0aDrug abusevTreatment. 0aDrug abusexTreatment. 0aLanguage and culture. 0aLanguagezUnited States. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aSELF-HELPvSubstance Abuse &ampxAddictionsvGeneral. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvAnthropologyvCultural. 0aSubstance-Related DisordersvtherapyzUnited States. 0aaddictionvfemmevsans-logisvEtats-Unis. 0aaddictionvinteraction verbalevrelation psychothérapeute-patientvEtats-Unis. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter